    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Style characterized by horizontally-oriented low buildings of one or two stories, flat roofs with little or no overhang, broad blank surfaces, few openings, components divided by small modules, materials of plaster, wood, brick, and tile, and colors in the ranges of reddish brown to cream. The style developed in Santa Fe, New Mexico, United States, as a statutory unified building style that incorporated synthesized elements of Pueblo Revival, Territorial, Native American, and American western styles, based on the Santa Fe Governor's Palace, Native American pueblos, and Spanish villages of the upper Rio Grande valley.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000036961/Sheppard, Creator of the Santa Fe Style (1987)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>以水平向延伸的低矮屋宇為特色之建築風格；此類建築樓高不超過兩層，具平式屋頂，有些屋頂會向外突出；其外牆寬廣無裝飾，少有窗面，建築構件間以小型材料區隔，建材包含灰漿、木材、磚、瓦等，色調則從紅棕色到乳白色皆涵蓋。此風格始自美國新墨西哥州的聖塔菲，乃政府統一制定，以聖塔菲總督府、美國原住民村落及里歐格蘭德河谷上游之西班牙村莊建築風格為基礎所發展，總共融合了普韋布洛復興風格（Pueblo Revival）、領地風格（Territorial）、美國印第安原住民及美國西部等風格。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
